Power analyses for OTM2

Frederik Aust

04 May, 2020

pes_to_dz <- function(pes, n, n_groups = 2) {
  # I *think* sqrt(n_groups) is needed because of the between subject factor
  # either way I validate that the results for pes, f, and dz are correct
  sqrt(((1 - n) * pes)/(n * (pes - 1))) * sqrt(n_groups)
}

dz_to_f <- function(dz, rho) {
  0.5 * dz * sqrt(2 * (1 - rho))
}

pes_to_f <- function(pes, n, rho) {
  dz <- pes_to_dz(pes, n)
  dz_to_f(dz, rho)
}

f_to_dz <- function(f, rho) {
  (sqrt(2) * f) / sqrt(1 - rho)
}

dz_to_pes <- function(dz, n, n_groups = 2) {
  (dz^2 * n)/(dz^2 * n + n*n_groups - n_groups)
}

Because it grants greater flexibility for ANOVA designs, I here used the in-development R package Superpower. The make sure I’m doing this right, I first reproduced the power analyses done in G*Power for OTM1.

1 OTM 1

The following gives the interaction power for the effect size estimated in the G*Power sensitivity analysis

However, this doesn’t give the result for the desired contrast that collapses over the counterbalancing factor, nor for a directional test. I contributed a pull request to Superpower to enable power analyses for contrasts specified with emmeans. The following gives the result for the collapsed contrast

custom_contrast <- contrast(
  emmeans(
    otm1_power$emmeans$emmeans
    , specs = ~ order * block
  )
  , list(block_effect = c(0.5, -0.5, -0.5, 0.5))
)

emmeans_power(custom_contrast, alpha_level = 0.05)
contrast power partial_eta_squared cohen_f non_centrality
block_effect 94.99999 0.0816906 0.2982577 13.16573

which is the same as doing a within-subject t-test in this case.

To simplify this, I will focus on the power for what we’d expect to be the smallest effect: The learning block contrast within each valence order group in IAT scores. Rydell et al. report the smallest contrast as \(\eta_p^2 = 0.1\) (\(d_z \approx 0.4666667\)), which is comparable in magnitude (but not direction) to the corresponding effect sizes reported by Heycke et al.

otm1_power <- function(f, rm_cor, n = 76, alpha = 0.05) {
  contrast_code <- tibble::tibble(
    a = rep(contr.sum(2), 2)
    , b = rep(contr.sum(2), each = 2)
    , x = a*b * -1
  )$x
  
  mu <- f * contrast_code

  cor_mat <- diag(4)
  triangular <- c(0, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0)
  cor_mat[upper.tri(cor_mat)] <- triangular * rm_cor
  cor_mat[lower.tri(cor_mat)] <- triangular * rm_cor
  
  string <- "2w*2b"
  labelnames <- c("block", "1", "2", "order", "n-p", "p-n")
  
  design_result <- ANOVA_design(
    design = string
    , n = n
    , mu = mu
    , sd = 1
    , r = cor_mat
    , labelnames = labelnames
  )
  
  otm1_power <- ANOVA_exact(
    design_result
    , alpha_level = alpha
    , emm = TRUE
    , verbose = FALSE
    , contrast_type = "pairwise"
    , emm_comp = "block | order"
  )
  
  otm1_power
}

Across all labs, our experimental design has 95% power to detect effects as small as \(\eta^2_p = .081\) (\(\delta_z = 0.4161869\)) and 80% power to detect effects as small as \(\eta^2_p = .050\) (\(\delta_z = 0.3234396\)). Figure 1.1 illustrates the implied Cohen’s \(\delta\) depending on the assumed repeated-measures correlation \(\rho\). That is, we have sufficient power to find (or rule out) effects approximately 20% smaller than the typical effects reported for the weakest contrast.

tibble(
  rho = rep(seq(-1, 1, length.out = 100), 2)
  , delta = c(
    dz_to_f(otm1_dz, unique(rho)) * 2

  )
  , power = rep(c("0.95", "0.80"), each = length(rho)/2)

  mutate(power = relevel(factor(power), "0.95")) %>%

2.1 By measure

Because Superpower only allows for power analyses, I manually determined the sample size that yields approximately 95% power. The following assumes that we are not interested in the effect of the counterbalancing factor order.

otm2_power <- function(f, n, rm_cor = 0.5, alpha = 0.05) {
  contrast_codes <- tibble::tibble(
    time = rep(contr.treatment(2), 4)
    , order = rep(rep(contr.sum(2), each = 2), 2)
    , block = rep(contr.sum(2), each = 4)
    , time_block = time * block
    , time_order = time * order
    , block_order = block * order
    , time_block_order = time * block * order
  )
  
  mu <- with(
    contrast_codes
    , -order * 0.25*f +
      -block_order * f
  )
  
  string <- "2w*2b*2b"
  labelnames <- c("block", "1", "2", "order", "p-n", "n-p", "time", "13", "20")
  
  design_result <- ANOVA_design(
    design = string
    , n = n
    , mu = mu
    , sd = 1
    , r = rm_cor
    , labelnames = labelnames
  )
  
  ANOVA_exact(
    design_result
    , alpha_level = alpha_level
    , emm = TRUE
    , verbose = FALSE
    , contrast_type = "pairwise"
    , emm_comp = "block | time * order"
  )
}

(ref:otm2-pes-plot) Sensitivity curves for OTM2. The simple contrast is the comparison of the two learning blocks within each presentation duration-valence order combination (not adjusted for multiple comparisons). Collapsed sensitivity curves apply to contrasts where data are pooled across either presentation duration or valence order (valence orders are pooled by reverse coding one order). \(\eta^2_p\)-values in the represent effect sizes corresponding to 95% and 80% power. The grey dashed line at the top represents the smallest learning block difference reported by Rydell et al. (2006).

2.1.1 Sensitivty for omnibus-tests

# Main effect block and three-way interaction
otm2_power <- function(f, n, rm_cor = 0.5, alpha = 0.05) {
  contrast_codes <- tibble::tibble(
    time = rep(contr.treatment(2), 4)
    , order = rep(rep(contr.sum(2), each = 2), 2)
    , block = rep(contr.sum(2), each = 4)
    , time_block = time * block
    , time_order = time * order
    , block_order = block * order
    , time_block_order = time * block * order
  )
  
  mu <- with(
    contrast_codes
    , #-order * 0.25*f +
      -block_order * f +
      -block * 0.5 * f +
      time_block_order * f
  )
  
  string <- "2w*2b*2b"
  labelnames <- c("block", "1", "2", "order", "p-n", "n-p", "time", "13", "20")
  
  design_result <- ANOVA_design(
    design = string
    , n = n
    , mu = mu
    , sd = 1
    , r = rm_cor
    , labelnames = labelnames
  )
  
  ANOVA_exact(
    design_result
    , alpha_level = alpha_level
    , emm = FALSE
    , verbose = FALSE
  )
}
